@NODE New_features "New features"
 - Allows selection of Archiver
 - Bulletins added to the packet
 - Welcome, News and Goodbye screens added to the packet
 - New files file in the packet
 - Easier @{" Individual " Link Individual} areas reset
 - Easier configuration
 - @{" Help " Link Help} in the packet
 - Personal messages index to make reading easier
 - configuration through messages (see @{" Message Configuration " Link Message_Configuration})

@ENDNODE

@NODE Main_Menu_commands "Main Menu commands"

 - [A]rchiver
 - [C]onfigure Areas
 - [D]ownload packet
 - [U]pload packet
 - [R]eset pointers
 - [H]elp
 - [V]ersion
 - [Q]uit to BBS


@ENDNODE

@NODE Archiver_Command "Archiver Command"
 This command allows you to select your preferrable archiver to use in your
 QWK packets. It shows all available archivers and shows the active one with
 an arrow. Just type your choice to change the active one.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Configure_Areas_command "Configure Areas command"
 Selecting this command will allow you to choose which areas you want to read.
 A list of all available areas that you have access will be shown, showing 
 their state of selected/unselected, denoted by an asterisk(*).
 To change the state of an area, just type its number in the prompt. It's a
 toggle selection mode. You can change the state of several areas. To do it,
 just type their numbers separated by spaces.
 
 Examples: 
 
 Suppose area 25 is not selected. So, if you type 25 followed by <ENTER>, 
 you'll get:
 Area AREANAME added. (where AREANAME is the area name)

 Suppose areas 10,12,13 are unselected and area 11 is selected. Typing 10 
 11 12 13<ENTER> will show:
 Area AREA10NAME added.
 Area AREA11NAME removed.
 Area AREA12NAME added.
 Area AREA13NAME added.

 Typing L at prompt will show you the list of all areas and their state.
 Typing C will deselect all areas and typing Q will return to the main menu.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Download_packet "Download packet"
 Selecting this will cause the program to create a QWK packet with all unread
 messages that you're allowed to read (those that aren't private or are 
 addressed to you). During the scan of messages, it will show how many 
 messages each area will have in the packet. After all areas are scanned, 
 the total number of messages will be shown (this number is limited by your 
 sysop), the number of personal messages, all the sysop files (screens, 
 newfiles, help, bulletins)  After this you'll be shown a prompt that allow you

 to:

 - change your transfer protocol
 - start the transfer
 - abort the transfer 

 To change the transfer protocol, type P at the prompt and after the list of
 available protocols, just type in the number of the desired protocol.
 To start the download just type S. The system will send you the packet. If it
 can't send it, it won't change your lastread pointers. If no error occured,
 your lastread pointers will be updated and your packet number will increase.
 Typing Q will return to the main menu.

 
@ENDNODE

@NODE Upload_packet "Upload packet"
 Selecting this will allow you to insert messages into the BBS. This option 
 has a prompt like the download one. Typing S will allow you to start the 
 transfer. After a packet is received, it will be decompressed and it's 
 messages will be put in their right places. During this, the program will 
 show you where the messages are going. After processing all messages in the 
 packet, the program will update the BBS pointers.

@{" NETMAIL " Link NETMAIL}
@{" PRIVATE AREAS " Link PRIVATE_AREAS}
@{" Message Configuration " Link Message_Configuration}
@ENDNODE

@NODE NETMAIL "NETMAIL"
 To insert a netmail, put the address at the beginning of the subject.
 Example:
 
 To: Carlos Almeida
 From: Francisco Moraes
 Subject: 4:801/31 This is a test
          ^^^^^^^^-> The address
 
 Attention: This will only work on a netmail area!
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE PRIVATE_AREAS "PRIVATE AREAS"
 There are some areas that only allow private messages. Any message saved
 by the program in this area will be private!

@ENDNODE

@NODE Message_Configuration "Message Configuration"
 This new version allows several message configuration options. They are
 divided into two ways, but they all are addressed to QMAIL. Case is not
 important.
 
@{" Direct " Link Direct}
@{" Indirect " Link Indirect}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Direct "Direct"
 In this way you just send one of the following commands in the subject filed,
 no matter what the message contain:

@{" ADD (direct) " Link ADD_(direct)}
@{" DROP (direct) " Link DROP_(direct)}
@{" RESET (direct) " Link RESET_(direct)}
@ENDNODE

@NODE ADD_(direct) "ADD (direct)"
 This command will add the message are where it was written to the QWK scan
 list. If an optional number after ADD is given, the door will reset the area's
 lastread pointer to that number (if positive one) or to the end minus the 
 specified number.
 
 Examples:
 
 (msg in area 10) ADD           will add area 10 to the scan list
 (msg in area  1) ADD 90        will add area 1 and set lastread pointer to 
                                message number 90
 (msg in area  5) ADD -10       will add area 5 and set lastread to msg number
                                end-10

@ENDNODE

@NODE DROP_(direct) "DROP (direct)"
 This command will remove an area from the scan list. It takes no arguments.
 
 Example:
 
 (msg in area 1) DROP           will remove area 1 from the scan list
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE RESET_(direct) "RESET (direct)"
 This command will reset an area lastread pointer to an specified value or to
 the end if no argument is given. A negative number will set lastread pointer
 to a number of messages below the end.
 
 Examples:
 
 (msg in area 2) RESET          resets area 2 lastread to the end
 (msg in area 3) RESET 10       resets area 3 lastread to msg 10
 (msg in area 4) RESET -20      resets area 4 lastread to 20 below the end
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE Indirect "Indirect"
 In this mode, you address the message to QMAIL and writes CONFIG in the
 subject field. This allows you to do:

@{" ADD (indirect) " Link ADD_(indirect)}
@{" DROP (indirect) " Link DROP_(indirect)}
@{" RESET (indirect) " Link RESET_(indirect)}
@{" PASSWORD " Link PASSWORD}
@{" ALIAS " Link ALIAS}
@{" BIRTH " Link BIRTH}
@{" CITY " Link CITY}
@{" COMP " Link COMP}
@{" HOTKEYS " Link HOTKEYS}
@{" LENGTH " Link LENGTH}
@{" PHONE " Link PHONE}
@{" POSTAL " Link POSTAL}
@{" PROV " Link PROV}
@{" STREET " Link STREET}
@ENDNODE

@NODE ADD_(indirect) "ADD (indirect)"
 Same as the direct ADD command, but it needs at least one argument: the messag

 area number. The second one works in the same way as in the direct ADD.
 
 Examples:
 
 ADD 1            adds area 1 to the scan list
 ADD 1 10         adds area 1 and sets pointer to msg number 10
 ADD 1 -10        adds area 1 and sets pointer to 10 below the end
 
 See also @{" ADD (direct) " Link ADD_(direct)}
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE DROP_(indirect) "DROP (indirect)"
 Same as the direct DROP command, but it needs one argument: the message area
 number.
 
 Example:
 
 DROP 1           removes area 1 from the scan list
 
 See also @{" DROP (direct) " Link DROP_(direct)}

@ENDNODE

@NODE RESET_(indirect) "RESET (indirect)"
 Same as the direct command, but it needs at least one argument as the
 previous two commands. The second one works like the direct RESET.
 
 Examples:
 
 RESET 1          resets area 1 pointer to the last msg
 RESET 1 10       resets area 1 pointer to msg number 10
 RESET 1 -10      resets area 1 pointer to 10 below the end of the area
 
 See also @{" RESET (direct) " Link RESET_(direct)}
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE PASSWORD "PASSWORD"
 This command allows you to change your password. The first word after the
 command will be taken as the password.
 
 Examples:
 
 PASSWORD CUPTEA     sets password to CUPTEA
 PASSWORD QWK DOOR   sets password to QWK

@ENDNODE

@NODE ALIAS "ALIAS"
 This allows you to change your handle (alias) used in the BBS. If your sysop
 allows handle yours will be changed to whatever comes after the command.
 There is no advice whether the command was successful or not.
 
 Example:
 
 ALIAS CHICO         sets handle to CHICO (if not in use)
 ALIAS STAR DUST     sets handle to STAR DUST (if not in use)
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE BIRTH "BIRTH"
 Changes your birthdate to the specified date. This should only be used if your
 data is wrong. The date MUST be in the same format used by the BBS: YYMMDD,
 where YY is the last two numbers of the year (padded with zeros if needed),
 MM is number of the month (padded with a zero if needed) and DD is the day 
 (padded with zero if needed)

 Example:
 
 BIRTH 740613         sets birthdate to June 13 1974

@ENDNODE

@NODE CITY "CITY"
 This allows you to change your city data. You should only use this if your 
 personal data is wrong or has changed.
 
 Examples:
 
 CITY Campinas        changes your city to Campinas
 CITY New York        changes your city to New York

@ENDNODE

@NODE COMP "COMP"
 This allows you to change your computer type.
 
 Examples:
 
 COMP Amiga 2000      changes your computer to Amiga 2000
 COMP Mac Quadra 950  changes your computer to Mac Quadra 950
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE HOTKEYS "HOTKEYS"
 This will change your command mode. If you pass 1 as arguments, hotkeys will
 be enabled. If you pass 0, hotkeys will be disabled and you will be able to
 stack commands.
 
 Examples:
 
 HOTKEYS 0             turns hotkeys off
 HOTKEYS 1             turns hotkeys on
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE LENGTH "LENGTH"
 This will change your screen size to the specified number. Be careful or you
 won't be able to read text in the BBS!
 
 Examples:
 
 LENGTH 0               will show you non-stopping text
 LENGTH 24              will set your screen size to 24 lines
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE PHONE "PHONE"
 This will change your phone number.
 
 Example:
 
 PHONE (0192) 33-2260   sets your phone number to (0192) 33-2260
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE POSTAL "POSTAL"
 Changes your postal zip code to the specified text.
 
 Example:
 
 POSTAL 13023-916       changes your zip code to 13023-916
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE PROV "PROV"
 Changes your province (state).
 
 Examples:
 
 PROV SP                changes your province data to SP
 PROV New Jersey        changes your province data to New Jersey
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE STREET "STREET"
 Changes your street address to the specified text.
 
 Example:
 
 STREET 986 5Th Street  changes your street address to 986 5Th Street
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE Reset_pointers "Reset pointers"
 This allow you to change your lastread pointers. You can change your pointers
 in two ways:


@{" Global " Link Global}
@{" Individual " Link Individual}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Global "Global"
 In this mode, you can change the lastread pointer of all selected areas. You
 can type -1 to reset to last message in every area, 0 to first message, any
 number to reset to that message number (if this number is higher than the
 high message in an area, the pointer will be set to the last one. If the
 number is below the first message, the pointer will be set to the first one) 
 If you simply type <RETURN> then no changes will be made.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE Individual "Individual"
 In this mode, you will be given the list of selected areas. As in the
 configure areas option, you can type a list of ares which you want to change
 the lastread pointer. Once you have done that, you'll be  prompted to change
 it for every area number you've typed. The program will show you the first
 and high messages in the area and your lastread pointer in that area. The
 options work in the same way as they do in the @{" Global " Link Global} reset.
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE Help "Help"
 This will only include the help file in the packet as BLT-0.99.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Version "Version"
 This shows some information about the program. It shows the copyright stuff 
 and the program version. If this is a registered copy, it will show the
 name of the registered user, together with his registration number.
 The message limit per packet will be shown, together with info telling 
 whether it's a sysop limit or unregistered version limit (10).
 The unregistered version has a limit of only 10 messages per packet. Ask 
 your sysop to register and help the author to make this program better.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Quit_to_BBS "Quit to BBS"
 This will save all of your configuration for the next time you use the 
 program and will return to the BBS.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Bugs "Bugs"
 This program haven't shown any bug up to now. Should it not work correctly,
 contact me or tell your sysop. There is no perfect program!
 
 See @{" How to contact the author " Link How_to_contact_the_author}

@ENDNODE

